Hey Maxie. Had a couple thoughts about your housing situation and ending up on a waiting list. Just wanted to pass them on.

1. I would reopen to the disability services office. Let them know that you will told not to apply until after your accommodations were confirmed and that you were then placed on a waiting list as a result. Disability Services can likely make the argument that that's discrimination and they might be able to get you a spot.

2. You could also consider contacting the ADA coordinator for Georgia Tech, Denise Marshall. She's generally a reasonable human being, at least from the couple interactions I've had with her. And she might be able to intervene with housing on your behalf, given the situation and how you were treated unfairly on account of your disability. ( And that you have some specific disability - related housing needs, including the need for a single apartment where you can have your esa)

I would just ask the office/person to look into the situation and let them come to that conclusion themselves. Basically, you just want to say, because of the way my disability accommodations were handled, I did not get a fair chance to apply for housing along with my peers. As a result, I ended up on a waiting list.

You can also state that, because of your disability, there are advantages for you in living on campus, if you think that is a fair argument. In your case, those advantages might include increased social support from peers living nearby and through RA-led programs. And there might be others I'm not thinking about.
